WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:10.000
In any case, let's back up a little bit and try to understand what's going on on what there is and in this last section of order of knowledge.

00:10.000 --> 00:23.000
We've looked at one criteria of ontological commitment and he puts it in a logistical approach to the ontological problem by saying that to be is to be a value of a variable.

00:23.000 --> 00:32.000
Well, he says it more explicitly or at least maybe less dramatically, but nevertheless more intelligently.

00:32.000 --> 00:35.000
But I think it's the same criteria in some of the way it works.

00:35.000 --> 00:38.000
And he then says, well, I'm not telling you what there is.

00:38.000 --> 00:42.000
I'm not trying to give you a theory of beating of what there is directly.

00:42.000 --> 00:44.000
I'm telling you what a theory says there is.

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
And so we might say, here's the idea.

00:48.000 --> 01:06.000
A theory says there are a's if and only if it asserts there are a's.

01:07.000 --> 01:15.000
Or in logical terms, there is an x subject able to prove x.

01:15.000 --> 01:19.000
Now, when you put it that way, it's almost trivial, right?

01:19.000 --> 01:22.000
When does a theory tell you there are certain objects?

01:22.000 --> 01:24.000
Well, when it says there are those objects.

01:24.000 --> 01:28.000
And so when he puts it that way, it should be clear.

01:28.000 --> 01:31.000
He's meaning to say something that's kind of obvious.

01:31.000 --> 01:38.000
Okay, when does my theory imply the existence of sense data when it says there are sense data?

01:38.000 --> 01:42.000
When does it imply the existence of unicorns when it says there are unicorns?

01:42.000 --> 01:46.000
When does it imply the existence of attributes when it says there are attributes?

01:46.000 --> 01:54.000
And so we look to things that we are willing to, well, quantify over in this sense, say there are such things.

01:54.000 --> 01:59.000
Now, put that way, it sounds like a very obvious point, right?

01:59.000 --> 02:03.000
But then the question is, well, okay, suppose that is the criterion.

02:03.000 --> 02:06.000
Notice it splits the ontological question in two.

02:06.000 --> 02:10.000
And that's something that isn't very obvious in the earlier work.

02:10.000 --> 02:13.000
It's something brought out by this reformulation.

02:13.000 --> 02:19.000
Because if we just say to be is to be a value of a variable, we think we're getting a theory of what there is, a theory of being.

02:19.000 --> 02:23.000
But if we say it this way, we realize there are really two questions.

02:23.000 --> 02:32.000
The first question is, okay, what does?

02:32.000 --> 02:36.000
Well, actually, this is telling you what a theory says there is.

02:36.000 --> 02:38.000
So why don't we start with a prior question?

02:38.000 --> 02:49.000
It's really, what theory about the world should we adopt?

02:49.000 --> 03:00.000
And then secondly, what does it say there is?

03:00.000 --> 03:05.000
In other words, he's really telling us what a theory claims about reality.

03:05.000 --> 03:08.000
What does a theory say there is in the world?

03:08.000 --> 03:13.000
And so if we're asking what is there in the world, really trying to address the fundamental question of ontology,

03:13.000 --> 03:16.000
we have to ask, well, first of all, what theory should we adopt?

03:16.000 --> 03:20.000
And then secondly, all right, what does it say there is?

03:20.000 --> 03:22.000
Now, let's look at that first question.

03:22.000 --> 03:24.000
What theory should we adopt?

03:24.000 --> 03:27.000
We're trying to describe the world, right?

03:27.000 --> 03:32.000
Well, a project of metaphysics is in a way to talk about the structure of the world.

03:32.000 --> 03:36.000
It's structure in the sense of what ultimately exists.

03:36.000 --> 03:39.000
How we talk about other things in terms of what ultimately exists.

03:39.000 --> 03:41.000
How the mind relates to all of that.

03:41.000 --> 03:44.000
All of that is broadly speaking metaphysics.

03:44.000 --> 03:48.000
At the bottom, we've got this ontological question of what there is.

03:48.000 --> 03:55.000
Well, in thinking about the world in this way, what sort of theory should we adopt?

03:55.000 --> 03:58.000
Where do we start in thinking about this?

03:58.000 --> 04:03.000
There are really only two options in Klein's view.

04:03.000 --> 04:06.000
Really maybe three, I guess I should say.

04:06.000 --> 04:11.000
But what are our options for this question of what theory we should adopt?

04:11.000 --> 04:13.000
Nominalism and realism?

04:13.000 --> 04:17.000
Well, we could adopt specific metaphysical theories like nominalism and realism.

04:17.000 --> 04:21.000
But in a sense, he's asking a question that's even prior to metaphysics.

04:21.000 --> 04:27.000
Prior to this question of what is real, like our attributes, universal forms, real or not.

04:27.000 --> 04:32.000
He's saying, look, I'm just trying to get a metaphysical theory of the world.

04:32.000 --> 04:35.000
And to do that, I just need to start with some theory of the world.

04:35.000 --> 04:38.000
I need to start with something that talks about the way the world is.

04:38.000 --> 04:40.000
And forget philosophy for a moment.

04:40.000 --> 04:43.000
It's not a question of starting with a philosophical theory.

04:43.000 --> 04:49.000
It's a question of just what are we, when we describe the world, what are we doing?

04:49.000 --> 04:51.000
He says science.

04:51.000 --> 04:54.000
Yeah, okay, one option here is science.

04:54.000 --> 04:57.000
And indeed, that's his preferred option.

04:57.000 --> 05:00.000
He says, yeah, we start with our best scientific theory.

05:00.000 --> 05:04.000
And then we ask what that scientific theory says there is.

05:04.000 --> 05:06.000
Well, that's one option.

05:06.000 --> 05:12.000
Say, yeah, look, when we're really about the project describing the world, we do science.

05:12.000 --> 05:14.000
And so we think science describes the world.

05:14.000 --> 05:20.000
And in his way of thinking about it, science is really, it's an old Aristotelian idea in a way.

05:20.000 --> 05:22.000
Science is like a layer page.

05:22.000 --> 05:27.000
So this picture of science he's working with, and it's a very common picture,

05:27.000 --> 05:35.000
is to say the most fundamental science, the one on which all the others rest, is physics.

05:35.000 --> 05:37.000
Physics, exactly.

05:37.000 --> 05:41.000
So physics is the thing that ultimately tells us what there is in the world.

05:41.000 --> 05:44.000
And then on top of physics, we build chemistry.

05:44.000 --> 05:48.000
And then on top of chemistry, we build biology.

05:48.000 --> 05:52.000
And on top of biology, we build psychology.

05:52.000 --> 05:58.000
And then on top of psychology, we build all the rest of the social sciences,

05:58.000 --> 06:01.000
things like economics, sociology, and so forth.

06:02.000 --> 06:09.000
And so if you have that picture of science, you're going to say, well, all right, yes,

06:09.000 --> 06:16.000
we talk about, for example, income trends and social groups and things like that.

06:16.000 --> 06:19.000
But in the end, those come down to questions of psychology.

06:19.000 --> 06:23.000
Those reduce to questions of biology, which in turn reduce to questions of chemistry,

06:23.000 --> 06:25.000
which ultimately reduce to physics.

06:25.000 --> 06:29.000
And so in the end, the way he talks about science, really,

06:29.000 --> 06:33.000
it becomes a question of what his physics state is.

06:33.000 --> 06:39.000
So as Quine's thinking about this question, we really start broadly speaking with the language of science

06:39.000 --> 06:42.000
and pretty quickly the language of physics.

06:42.000 --> 06:47.000
I have a question about scientific language philosophers in general.

06:47.000 --> 06:54.000
When you read someone like Stephen Hawking, he explicitly admits that all these things he's talking about

06:54.000 --> 06:56.000
don't necessarily really exist.

06:56.000 --> 06:58.000
They're mathematical models.

06:58.000 --> 07:02.000
When you're talking about like Einstein radiation or something like that,

07:02.000 --> 07:06.000
it's not like there's some entity there.

07:06.000 --> 07:11.000
This ground state fluctuations are a model to describe a phenomenon.

07:11.000 --> 07:17.000
How do these scientific language philosophers square their theories with that?

07:17.000 --> 07:19.000
Great question.

07:19.000 --> 07:22.000
When we look at science, notice it's doing something,

07:22.000 --> 07:26.000
well, at the higher levels, it may just be much of the time anyway,

07:26.000 --> 07:30.000
we're just systematizing things that we already think are there.

07:30.000 --> 07:36.000
But when we get down to these levels, science is postulating a realm of hypothetical entities,

07:36.000 --> 07:40.000
theoretical entities, that we don't have any access to in observation.

07:40.000 --> 07:44.000
Things like microparticles, things like fields of certain kinds,

07:44.000 --> 07:53.000
or in string theory, strings, maybe in theories of additional dimensions and things like that, hyperspace.

07:53.000 --> 07:58.000
In the end, we've got certain objects, and indeed physics is quantifying over certain objects.

07:58.000 --> 08:01.000
Well, what sort of objects?

08:01.000 --> 08:03.000
And what do we say about those?

08:03.000 --> 08:07.000
There are going to be entities here, but now there are two attitudes you might have about them.

08:07.000 --> 08:16.000
You might be a realist who says, look, science says there are quarks, for example,

08:16.000 --> 08:18.000
and that's our best scientific theory of the world.

08:18.000 --> 08:22.000
It asserts that there are quarks, so I have reason to believe there are quarks.

08:22.000 --> 08:27.000
And so the realist says the real objects, especially if he goes the path of flying here,

08:27.000 --> 08:30.000
the real objects are just the objects postulated by science.

08:30.000 --> 08:32.000
So in the end, what is there in the world?

08:32.000 --> 08:39.000
Well, there are things like quarks and electromagnetic fields, and positrons, and neutrons, and so forth.

08:39.000 --> 08:45.000
On the other hand, there's another attitude you might have towards science, an instrumentalist attitude,

08:45.000 --> 08:51.000
which says, wait a minute, I'm postulating entities like quarks and fields and so on.

08:51.000 --> 08:57.000
But to those things really exist, I'm saying they're useful calculating devices.

08:57.000 --> 09:02.000
So one way of looking at it is the realist says, look, these basic objects of science,

09:02.000 --> 09:10.000
let's call them theoretical objects, the theoretical objects exist,

09:10.000 --> 09:15.000
and the scientific theory explains what it explains if those things exist.

09:15.000 --> 09:18.000
But if they don't exist, there's something weird going on.

09:18.000 --> 09:21.000
You've got something that's really just a calculating device.

09:21.000 --> 09:25.000
The instrumentalist says, well, yeah, that's all it is. It is a calculated device.

09:25.000 --> 09:33.000
And so the instrumentalist says, wait a minute, this whole idea of answering science is not going to give us the right answer.

09:33.000 --> 09:40.000
What science does is hypothesize various things that might be behind the curtain to explain the appearances we have in the world.

09:40.000 --> 09:45.000
But don't think those things being postulated as being behind the curtain are the real things.

09:45.000 --> 09:49.000
They're just ways of calculating about the things we actually experience.

09:49.000 --> 09:56.000
So the instrumentalist is going to say, look, don't take physics or science in general as the right way to do this.

09:56.000 --> 09:58.000
It's not telling you what they're all about.

09:58.000 --> 10:03.000
Yeah, it seems like the realist would run into immediate problems with no light.

10:03.000 --> 10:11.000
Science says it's a particle and a wave, and those things are mutually exclusive if you take it in a realistic way.

10:11.000 --> 10:16.000
We have to kind of view it as a mathematical, as an instrumentalist view.

10:16.000 --> 10:21.000
And I think most physicists I've read seem to be more instrumentalists.

10:21.000 --> 10:26.000
Right, lots of physicists are instrumentalists, partly because it's a way of avoiding carbon problems.

10:26.000 --> 10:30.000
Like, are you saying that light is really a particle or is it a wave?

10:30.000 --> 10:33.000
Is it some kind of weird combination of the two?

10:33.000 --> 10:37.000
Some people have introduced this sort of a waveical for it, right?

10:37.000 --> 10:42.000
And the realist has to grapple with those questions and says roughly after quantum mechanics,

10:42.000 --> 10:44.000
yeah, this is what really is in the world.

10:44.000 --> 10:46.000
You know what, the world is weird, man.

10:46.000 --> 10:48.000
The world is unbelievably dear.

10:48.000 --> 10:53.000
And indeed, the realist often says, yes, physics is describing the way the world is.

10:53.000 --> 10:56.000
Ultimately, quantum mechanics is describing what the possible is in the world.

10:56.000 --> 10:57.000
It turns out it's weird.

10:57.000 --> 10:59.000
It doesn't fit our ordinary chemical words at all.

10:59.000 --> 11:02.000
So it's very easy to go from this claim, a theoretical object,

11:02.000 --> 11:07.000
so that the ones that really exist to say, look, the world is weird.

11:07.000 --> 11:13.000
And a lot of physicists want to say, hmm, I don't know if the world is really that weird.

11:13.000 --> 11:17.000
We've got a theory here that works really well, but it might be.

11:17.000 --> 11:19.000
And indeed, if we think it's just a calculating device,

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
does it have to give us a picture of what light really is?

11:22.000 --> 11:24.000
It doesn't have to answer that question.

11:24.000 --> 11:26.000
You can say it in certain respects, it's like a particle.

11:26.000 --> 11:28.000
In certain other respects, it's like a wave.

11:28.000 --> 11:31.000
We've got the famous two-slit experiments,

11:31.000 --> 11:34.000
and it's very hard to make sense of the intuitive terms.

11:34.000 --> 11:39.000
But from this point of view, good, we don't have to make sense of the intuitive terms.

11:39.000 --> 11:44.000
It's a mathematical theory, and it explains the appearances.

11:44.000 --> 11:47.000
And the appearances are kind of strange and surprising.

11:47.000 --> 11:51.000
But nevertheless, we don't take the object seriously.

11:51.000 --> 11:55.000
Now, if we have this attitude, we're not going to say science is the path to this,

11:55.000 --> 11:57.000
and that's the theory, not the theory we're going to be interested in.

11:57.000 --> 12:02.000
What will we be interested in?

12:02.000 --> 12:05.000
I mean, if we're instrumentalists about the objects introduced by science,

12:05.000 --> 12:11.000
hypothetically, and theoretically, then what are we taking as fundamental?

12:11.000 --> 12:13.000
What we see.

12:13.000 --> 12:14.000
What we see, yeah.

12:14.000 --> 12:16.000
So science is one option.

12:16.000 --> 12:18.000
But there are other options.

12:18.000 --> 12:22.000
One option would be, well, experience.

12:22.000 --> 12:25.000
The objects of immediate experience.

12:25.000 --> 12:28.000
So we've seen some philosophers who do that.

12:28.000 --> 12:33.000
Okay, Russell, for example, talking about sense data,

12:33.000 --> 12:41.000
or actually Karnam in the logical structure of the world,

12:41.000 --> 12:45.000
and arguing that you can reduce all talk of physical objects

12:45.000 --> 12:48.000
to objects of immediate sensation, something like sense data.

12:48.000 --> 12:51.000
What's right before your senses at any given moment?

12:51.000 --> 12:54.000
He also argues in that book, you can do it the other way around.

12:54.000 --> 12:58.000
You can reduce talk of sense data to talk of physical objects.

12:58.000 --> 13:00.000
And then he says, which should we take as primary?

13:00.000 --> 13:04.000
Should we really think what there is in the world are physical objects?

13:04.000 --> 13:08.000
Or should we think, no, it's a matter of the contents of immediate experience.

13:08.000 --> 13:10.000
It's sensations.

13:10.000 --> 13:15.000
And he ends up saying, you can do it either way, which is a little surprising.

13:15.000 --> 13:18.000
But he says, what's directly before the mind,

13:18.000 --> 13:22.000
and so what's epistemologically prior, are the sensations.

13:22.000 --> 13:25.000
So he favors actually going in the direction of the sensations.

13:25.000 --> 13:27.000
But he admits it goes both ways.

13:27.000 --> 13:30.000
And part of what's in the background, in object decision,

13:30.000 --> 13:34.000
that last section of word and object, is that Klein assumes you know Karnam.

13:34.000 --> 13:37.000
And Klein is basically saying, yes, you can go in either direction.

13:37.000 --> 13:42.000
But I favor, he says, going in the direction of taking physical objects as primary.

13:42.000 --> 13:45.000
But not ordinary physical objects like tables and chairs,

13:45.000 --> 13:49.000
necessarily in the end, the objects are hypothesized by science.

13:49.000 --> 13:53.000
He's aware that Karnam and Russell and others would say, no, no, no,

13:53.000 --> 13:55.000
go in this more instrumentalist direction.

13:55.000 --> 13:58.000
And that's going to lead me to say it's experience that's the fundamental

13:58.000 --> 14:00.000
theory I don't worry about.

14:00.000 --> 14:03.000
And my reports of sensations.

14:03.000 --> 14:05.000
And he says, we could do it that way.

14:05.000 --> 14:10.000
But he thinks that our theory of objects in the world is just so well confirmed

14:10.000 --> 14:12.000
and so explanatory.

14:12.000 --> 14:16.000
Then he says, look, I know how to get through a day without referring to my own sensations.

14:16.000 --> 14:19.000
I don't know how to get through a day without referring to people and tables

14:19.000 --> 14:23.000
and chairs and other ordinary objects of experience.

14:23.000 --> 14:30.000
And so he ends up saying, I'd much rather trust talk of objects than talk of sensations.

14:30.000 --> 14:32.000
But there's yet another option.

14:32.000 --> 14:42.000
What other option could there be?

14:42.000 --> 14:45.000
When you talk about the world, sometimes you do science.

14:45.000 --> 14:47.000
Sometimes you might be talking about your own experiences.

14:47.000 --> 14:52.000
But what do we do most of the time?

14:52.000 --> 14:55.000
I say, tell me about this room.

14:55.000 --> 15:02.000
Do you immediately start saying, well, all right, let's introduce the wave function.

15:02.000 --> 15:04.000
Our observations?

15:04.000 --> 15:06.000
Well, you could be talking about our observations.

15:06.000 --> 15:08.000
I mean, you could say, ah, tell me about the room.

15:08.000 --> 15:19.000
Well, I'm sensing grayly and greenly and clockly and camera-ly and people-ly.

15:19.000 --> 15:21.000
But you probably don't, right?

15:21.000 --> 15:22.000
What do you do?

15:22.000 --> 15:23.000
Yeah.

15:23.000 --> 15:24.000
Perceptimals.

15:24.000 --> 15:25.000
Yeah, exactly.

15:25.000 --> 15:28.000
In other words, the objects of ordinary perception, right?

15:28.000 --> 15:30.000
I look around saying, oh, what's in the room?

15:30.000 --> 15:32.000
Sure, I'll describe the room for you.

15:32.000 --> 15:35.000
It's got tile on the floor and a bunch of desks and there are people in the desks

15:35.000 --> 15:39.000
and it's got clock at the back and blackboards all around and so forth and so on.

15:39.000 --> 15:42.000
And I tell you about the ordinary objects of experience.

15:42.000 --> 15:45.000
And so you might say, well, look, one place to look is science.

15:45.000 --> 15:50.000
One place to look is the contents of experience in the sense of these sensations themselves.

15:50.000 --> 15:54.000
But another place to look is just our everyday language, right?

15:54.000 --> 16:02.000
So we can say, just look at natural language and our everyday uses of it.

16:02.000 --> 16:07.000
After all, we ordinarily confront the world not just by talking about our own sensations,

16:07.000 --> 16:10.000
not by doing science, but just by talking about stuff.

16:10.000 --> 16:12.000
Go to lunch with somebody after class.

16:12.000 --> 16:14.000
But what are you going to talk about?

16:14.000 --> 16:16.000
I mean, maybe you're going to talk about physics.

16:16.000 --> 16:21.000
Except you say, whoa, check out that electron.

16:21.000 --> 16:25.000
Maybe you're going to talk about your own sensations.

16:25.000 --> 16:29.000
I mean, I suppose that's actually plausible in certain settings.

16:29.000 --> 16:32.000
People talk about their feelings and all that.

16:32.000 --> 16:35.000
But often, you're not talking about your feelings or other sensations.

16:35.000 --> 16:37.000
You're not talking about physics.

16:37.000 --> 16:41.000
You're talking about things and people around you.

16:41.000 --> 16:45.000
And so that might be a place to start.

16:45.000 --> 16:49.000
Now, the reason I mentioned that is that a lot of clients' effort in word and object

16:49.000 --> 16:53.000
is to actually say, yeah, but don't worry about that.

16:53.000 --> 16:56.000
We can explain the kinds of things we talk about there.

16:56.000 --> 17:00.000
And if pushed to the wall, he ends up saying, well, anyway, they're not part of science,

17:00.000 --> 17:02.000
so I don't have to worry about them.

17:02.000 --> 17:04.000
But he doesn't start there.

17:04.000 --> 17:08.000
If he really started there, he'd just say, here's the language in physics.

17:08.000 --> 17:10.000
And here's what it's telling us.

17:10.000 --> 17:11.000
He doesn't do that.

17:11.000 --> 17:17.000
He talks about attributes and propositions and facts and models and glids and all these other things.

17:17.000 --> 17:19.000
And why is he doing that?

17:19.000 --> 17:21.000
Because we talk about the natural language.

17:21.000 --> 17:25.000
And he feels compelled to say something about what we really have to be committed to.

17:25.000 --> 17:30.000
Because he doesn't want to say that much of what we say is just false.

17:30.000 --> 17:34.000
I say, well, I didn't see the light.

17:34.000 --> 17:38.000
There was this glint of a mirror, a neighboring car.

17:38.000 --> 17:41.000
And we don't want to be lying.

17:41.000 --> 17:46.000
The officer might not believe you, but the officer isn't going to say,

17:46.000 --> 17:48.000
yeah, listen, I've written word and object.

17:48.000 --> 17:50.000
There are no such things as glints.

17:50.000 --> 17:53.000
No, he's saying it's false.

17:53.000 --> 17:57.000
We want to be able to make some sense of that kind of talk.

17:57.000 --> 18:00.000
OK, so those are the options that are in front of us.

18:00.000 --> 18:05.000
And then why, now, he doesn't really, although that's his ultimate position,

18:05.000 --> 18:07.000
he doesn't just jump there.

18:07.000 --> 18:10.000
He tries to actually say, look, most of the time,

18:10.000 --> 18:15.000
we don't have to worry about the things that natural language introduces

18:15.000 --> 18:17.000
in addition to the language of science.

18:17.000 --> 18:21.000
So what does science really commit us to in his view?

18:21.000 --> 18:23.000
Two things in that, right?

18:23.000 --> 18:27.000
Well, two very broad categories of things.

18:27.000 --> 18:32.000
What are they?

18:32.000 --> 18:40.000
What does science talk about?

18:40.000 --> 18:43.000
See, be brave.

18:43.000 --> 18:45.000
Good physical objects, exactly.

18:45.000 --> 18:49.000
I'm not looking for something deep like, oh, man, I forgot my hyperspace theory.

18:49.000 --> 18:51.000
Yes, physical objects.

18:51.000 --> 18:52.000
OK, good.

18:52.000 --> 18:55.000
So yes, it talks about physical objects.

18:55.000 --> 18:58.000
And what else does it use in talking about physical objects?

18:58.000 --> 19:00.000
Abstract objects.

19:00.000 --> 19:02.000
Abstract objects, exactly.

