35:10.000 --> 35:12.000
But in the end, I thought philosophically,

35:12.000 --> 35:14.000
it made no sense.

35:14.000 --> 35:16.000
So in any event, that's why I, too,

35:16.000 --> 35:20.000
stopped being an analyst at a little confession time.

35:20.000 --> 35:24.000
But anyway, Kwan didn't really take that detour.

35:24.000 --> 35:26.000
He just said, yeah, it seems to me

35:26.000 --> 35:28.000
what we've learned from the paradoxes.

35:28.000 --> 35:30.000
And the way of reformulating mathematics

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
in the life of the paradoxes is you can't get rid of

35:32.000 --> 35:35.000
a commitment to abstract objects.

35:35.000 --> 35:39.000
You end up having to commit yourself to sets.

35:39.000 --> 35:45.000
Now, I see that excited a few of you

35:45.000 --> 35:47.000
and bored to tears the rest of you.

35:47.000 --> 35:51.000
So let's go back to the objects that might be introduced,

35:51.000 --> 35:54.000
not by science, but by, for example, natural language.

35:54.000 --> 35:56.000
So he's worried about these things.

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
And in the end, he says, yes, these things

35:58.000 --> 36:00.000
we have to be committed to before to do science.

36:00.000 --> 36:03.000
So he thinks those really do answer the question,

36:03.000 --> 36:04.000
what is there?

36:04.000 --> 36:05.000
What is there?

36:05.000 --> 36:07.000
In the end, the physical objects, as described by physics,

36:07.000 --> 36:09.000
and sets.

36:09.000 --> 36:12.000
But now, what else might we worry about?

36:12.000 --> 36:16.000
Well, one thing that he's concerned about is actual use.

36:16.000 --> 36:17.000
Right?

36:17.000 --> 36:20.000
In other words, proverbs.

36:20.000 --> 36:27.000
Or more broadly, relations, et cetera.

36:27.000 --> 36:32.000
Do we have to think that those things exist?

36:32.000 --> 36:35.000
Well, last time, we looked at some examples,

36:35.000 --> 36:45.000
like the clock has rattles.

36:45.000 --> 36:49.000
We could existentially quantify it,

36:49.000 --> 36:51.000
so the clock has something.

36:51.000 --> 36:52.000
Remember that inference?

36:52.000 --> 36:54.000
Actually, I think we talked about pebbles,

36:54.000 --> 36:58.000
which is an example of what there is.

36:58.000 --> 37:00.000
What should we do about that?

37:00.000 --> 37:07.000
Doesn't it follow that, therefore, the clock has something?

37:07.000 --> 37:17.000
In which case, we're committed to attributes.

37:17.000 --> 37:19.000
If you're already committed to abstract objects,

37:19.000 --> 37:23.000
why is committing to attributes as abstract objects

37:23.000 --> 37:25.000
extend your anthropology?

37:25.000 --> 37:27.000
That's a great question.

37:27.000 --> 37:30.000
You might think, look, there are places to man the barricades

37:30.000 --> 37:33.000
philosophically, and places not.

37:34.000 --> 37:37.000
You might think, indeed, the nominalists think,

37:37.000 --> 37:40.000
typically, abstract objects are the place to do it.

37:40.000 --> 37:41.000
Universals.

37:41.000 --> 37:43.000
By the way, Quine conflates those two issues.

37:43.000 --> 37:45.000
There really are separate issues.

37:45.000 --> 37:48.000
The abstract concrete distinction and the universal

37:48.000 --> 37:50.000
particular distinction are not the same distinction.

37:50.000 --> 37:52.000
He recognizes that in word and object.

37:52.000 --> 37:55.000
He says, oh yeah, there are these kind of abstract

37:55.000 --> 37:57.000
particulars like the equator.

37:57.000 --> 37:58.000
Whatever.

37:58.000 --> 38:00.000
Let's go on to typical cases.

38:00.000 --> 38:02.000
But anyway, that aside, you might think,

38:02.000 --> 38:04.000
yeah, look, abstract and concrete,

38:04.000 --> 38:06.000
that's a big place to draw the fighting line.

38:06.000 --> 38:08.000
After all, concrete objects are ones

38:08.000 --> 38:10.000
I can come into contact with.

38:10.000 --> 38:12.000
Maybe I can experience them.

38:12.000 --> 38:14.000
At any rate, I can come into some kind of causal

38:14.000 --> 38:16.000
contact with them, even some micro-particle

38:16.000 --> 38:18.000
that I could never directly experience,

38:18.000 --> 38:20.000
causally interact with me.

38:20.000 --> 38:23.000
And I can have a theory of that causal interaction.

38:23.000 --> 38:26.000
So concrete objects, I'm happy to admit into my

38:26.000 --> 38:29.000
ontology because I'm interacting with them all the time.

38:29.000 --> 38:31.000
And I explain how, therefore, I can know about them.

38:32.000 --> 38:34.000
But an abstract object isn't the kind of thing

38:34.000 --> 38:36.000
I can causally interact with.

38:36.000 --> 38:38.000
It's not just that I can't experience it.

38:38.000 --> 38:41.000
I don't see roundness in the way that I see

38:41.000 --> 38:43.000
the clock, for example.

38:43.000 --> 38:46.000
But also, and I don't see the number three,

38:46.000 --> 38:49.000
for example, I might see three birds on a wire.

38:49.000 --> 38:51.000
And so you might think, yeah, look,

38:51.000 --> 38:53.000
I don't experience these.

38:53.000 --> 38:55.000
I don't have causal contact with them.

38:55.000 --> 38:57.000
And so this is a place to fight.

38:57.000 --> 38:59.000
But once I've lost that fight,

38:59.000 --> 39:01.000
once I have to recognize sense,

39:01.000 --> 39:03.000
you might say, now, why not just

39:03.000 --> 39:05.000
in for a penny, in for a pound?

39:05.000 --> 39:07.000
I've already got sense.

39:07.000 --> 39:09.000
I've already made that purchase.

39:09.000 --> 39:11.000
Why not go ahead and buy the full package

39:11.000 --> 39:14.000
and get HBO and Cinemax 2 as a word?

39:14.000 --> 39:16.000
Might as well get attributes.

39:16.000 --> 39:19.000
It might as well sign on for propositions

39:19.000 --> 39:21.000
and facts and all the rest of it.

39:21.000 --> 39:24.000
Because after all, they're a small additional cost.

39:24.000 --> 39:27.000
Not true in the case of movie packages.

39:27.000 --> 39:29.000
But you might think it is true.

39:29.000 --> 39:31.000
Here, Fimmelsoff, why not?

39:31.000 --> 39:34.000
Now, I think that's a great question.

39:34.000 --> 39:36.000
Why does Quine spend a lot of time

39:36.000 --> 39:38.000
worrying about these?

39:38.000 --> 39:40.000
Two parts to the question, really.

39:40.000 --> 39:42.000
If science is what tells us what there is,

39:42.000 --> 39:44.000
who cares what we say in natural language?

39:44.000 --> 39:46.000
And second part of the question is,

39:46.000 --> 39:49.000
once you've, in effect, admitted these,

39:49.000 --> 39:51.000
now, why should it matter to you

39:51.000 --> 39:54.000
whether there are additional kinds of abstract objects

39:54.000 --> 39:57.000
like attributes and relations and propositions

39:57.000 --> 40:00.000
and meanings and so on?

40:00.000 --> 40:02.000
Because they're different, right?

40:02.000 --> 40:03.000
They are different.

40:03.000 --> 40:04.000
Now, how are they different?

40:04.000 --> 40:06.000
Why does he really resist them?

40:06.000 --> 40:08.000
Because we love the dog.

40:08.000 --> 40:10.000
Okay, good.

40:10.000 --> 40:14.000
Like, doghood is completely different

40:14.000 --> 40:17.000
from saying that this is a dog, an individual dog,

40:17.000 --> 40:19.000
and then you have another individual dog, right?

40:19.000 --> 40:21.000
Right.

40:21.000 --> 40:22.000
Okay, good.

40:22.000 --> 40:24.000
Now, Quine says that he's looking for something

40:24.000 --> 40:26.000
that's explanatory.

40:26.000 --> 40:28.000
And he says, are physical explanations

40:28.000 --> 40:29.000
involve physical objects?

40:29.000 --> 40:31.000
They involve mathematics.

40:31.000 --> 40:35.000
But I don't think this explains anything, okay?

40:35.000 --> 40:36.000
In other words, he said,

40:36.000 --> 40:38.000
and in part is a willingness to say,

40:38.000 --> 40:41.000
I'm happy to recognize

40:41.000 --> 40:44.000
ontological commitments where something is introduced

40:44.000 --> 40:46.000
to explain the experiences I have,

40:46.000 --> 40:49.000
to explain the appearances, to explain the world.

40:49.000 --> 40:51.000
But I don't think introducing a form like roundness

40:51.000 --> 40:53.000
does any explaining at all.

40:53.000 --> 40:55.000
You say, aha, the clock is round.

40:55.000 --> 40:56.000
Why is the clock round?

40:56.000 --> 40:58.000
The answer is, well, it has roundness.

40:58.000 --> 41:01.000
Do I learn anything from that?

41:01.000 --> 41:03.000
Does it explain anything?

41:03.000 --> 41:05.000
I think his answer is no.

41:05.000 --> 41:08.000
And so the way he sees it, it's like this.

41:08.000 --> 41:10.000
I've got two ways of putting things.

41:10.000 --> 41:17.000
I can say the clock is round.

41:17.000 --> 41:24.000
Or I can say the clock has roundness.

41:24.000 --> 41:26.000
And now he's saying,

41:26.000 --> 41:29.000
which one of those is explanatory prime?

41:29.000 --> 41:32.000
Does the clock have roundness because it's round?

41:32.000 --> 41:35.000
Or is the clock round because it has roundness?

41:35.000 --> 41:36.000
What should I say?

41:36.000 --> 41:40.000
Which of those is more fundamental?

41:40.000 --> 41:46.000
Which gives me an explanation.

41:46.000 --> 41:48.000
The clock is round.

41:48.000 --> 41:49.000
Yeah, exactly.

41:49.000 --> 41:51.000
He says, look, the clock is round.

41:51.000 --> 41:54.000
That's the thing that explains this other thing, right?

41:54.000 --> 41:56.000
Why do I say it has roundness?

41:56.000 --> 41:58.000
Because it's round.

41:58.000 --> 42:00.000
That's the fundamental thing.

42:00.000 --> 42:04.000
And saying it has roundness doesn't explain anything at all.

42:04.000 --> 42:07.000
In fact, there's a sort of paradox you can keep going.

42:07.000 --> 42:09.000
Why does it have roundness?

42:09.000 --> 42:12.000
Because it has the property of having roundness.

42:12.000 --> 42:16.000
Or it and roundness are in the participation margin.

42:16.000 --> 42:19.000
And so if you start making this move,

42:19.000 --> 42:21.000
this is something called the Bradley Regress.

42:21.000 --> 42:23.000
You might worry it keeps going.

42:23.000 --> 42:25.000
And a lot of nominalists have been motivated

42:25.000 --> 42:27.000
by that Bradley Regress thinking,

42:27.000 --> 42:29.000
I don't know where it stops.

42:29.000 --> 42:33.000
If the clock is round, something like RC

42:33.000 --> 42:38.000
is explained by C having R-ness,

42:38.000 --> 42:41.000
that it seems like now I've got the relation of having

42:41.000 --> 42:45.000
linking C and roundness.

42:45.000 --> 42:47.000
And then you might say, oh, now I've got

42:47.000 --> 42:51.000
some other special relation linking having

42:51.000 --> 42:54.000
and C and roundness.

42:54.000 --> 42:58.000
And well, you can see I can just keep doing this forever.

42:58.000 --> 43:03.000
But even if you say, well, maybe I can stop this regress here,

43:03.000 --> 43:05.000
it's not clear what that's accomplishing.

43:05.000 --> 43:07.000
So I think that's part of his reason.

43:07.000 --> 43:09.000
He thinks this isn't doing any explaining.

43:09.000 --> 43:11.000
It's really derivative.

43:11.000 --> 43:15.000
And there are other reasons too.

43:15.000 --> 43:19.000
How do I know how to talk about roundness?

43:19.000 --> 43:23.000
It's epistemologically by virtue of interacting with round things.

43:23.000 --> 43:26.000
So the explanatory priority of this

43:26.000 --> 43:28.000
is mirrored by its epistemic priority.

43:28.000 --> 43:31.000
I encounter the clock and I see that it's round.

43:31.000 --> 43:34.000
I don't encounter roundness in the same way.

43:34.000 --> 43:37.000
It seems indirect by virtue of encountering round things.

43:37.000 --> 43:41.000
And so you might say, I say this after learning

43:41.000 --> 43:43.000
the talk of properties and attributes and so on,

43:43.000 --> 43:47.000
because I think that's not the other way around.

43:47.000 --> 43:50.000
The little baby doesn't start speaking as a Platonist.

43:50.000 --> 43:53.000
Oh, Mama exemplified here.

43:53.000 --> 43:56.000
But instead talks about Mama, OK?

43:56.000 --> 44:01.000
And we'll learn to say, you know, green or something.

44:01.000 --> 44:05.000
And so anyway, he's motivated in part by that.

44:05.000 --> 44:09.000
Well, he thinks we can get rid of talk of meanings

44:09.000 --> 44:11.000
of propositions of attributes.

44:11.000 --> 44:13.000
And here's one way to do it, right?

44:13.000 --> 44:14.000
The clock has roundness.

44:14.000 --> 44:15.000
Oh, very easy.

44:15.000 --> 44:17.000
Just translate that into the clock is round.

44:17.000 --> 44:19.000
Now what about this?

44:19.000 --> 44:26.000
Roundness is an attribute.

44:26.000 --> 44:33.000
How do we get rid of that?

44:33.000 --> 44:36.000
After all, roundness in that sort of having round this position,

44:36.000 --> 44:38.000
that's easy to replace with a predicate.

44:38.000 --> 44:40.000
But here we've got a subject position.

44:40.000 --> 44:43.000
If Quine's right, we can rephrase all of these things.

44:43.000 --> 44:45.000
And notice in the logic decision chapter,

44:45.000 --> 44:48.000
he really, for that matter, on what there is,

44:48.000 --> 44:50.000
he gives you a few examples, but he doesn't give you

44:50.000 --> 44:52.000
any programmatic way of doing this.

44:52.000 --> 44:54.000
So we've got to be creative here.

44:54.000 --> 44:57.000
It's not like he tells us how to do most of this stuff.

44:57.000 --> 44:59.000
He just gives us a couple of examples and says, see?

44:59.000 --> 45:08.000
But now here, what could we do?

45:08.000 --> 45:09.000
Yeah.

45:09.000 --> 45:12.000
Is this maybe a good example of you turning roundness into a verb?

45:12.000 --> 45:17.000
Like roundness is kind of doing a certain work,

45:17.000 --> 45:20.000
like theoretically and trying to explain it.

45:20.000 --> 45:21.000
Yes.

45:21.000 --> 45:22.000
That's true.

45:22.000 --> 45:24.000
And so one way to do it would be to say,

45:24.000 --> 45:26.000
well, here our strategy was to replace

45:26.000 --> 45:28.000
talk of roundness with talk of round things.

45:28.000 --> 45:30.000
So maybe we could say round things.

45:30.000 --> 45:32.000
Oh, we don't want to say have an attribute.

45:32.000 --> 45:35.000
We could say round things are blank for some blank.

45:35.000 --> 45:38.000
Or another way to do it, the way Carnap does it actually

45:38.000 --> 45:40.000
in the logical syntax of language,

45:40.000 --> 45:42.000
is to go into what he calls the formal mode

45:42.000 --> 45:44.000
by what Quine later calls semantic ascent.

45:44.000 --> 45:53.000
So this is just saying round is imaginative.

45:53.000 --> 45:55.000
Which is a little weird because there we replace it

45:55.000 --> 45:57.000
with round things, and here we replace it with round.

45:57.000 --> 46:00.000
But that might be less strange if we think here

46:00.000 --> 46:08.000
we're really saying, well, the word round is true of the clock.

46:08.000 --> 46:10.000
Well, in the closing moment here,

46:10.000 --> 46:12.000
let me just say something about how he gets rid of meanings.

46:12.000 --> 46:17.000
Because this ends up being a major strategy for Quine.

46:17.000 --> 46:19.000
How do we get rid of meanings?

46:19.000 --> 46:22.000
Instead of talking about the meaning of a sentence,

46:22.000 --> 46:24.000
he says we can just replace that with, first of all,

46:24.000 --> 46:26.000
the talk of the sentence being meaningful.

46:26.000 --> 46:31.000
So first of all, you draw a distinction between the meaningful

46:31.000 --> 46:35.000
and the insignificant, the meaningless, I suppose.

46:35.000 --> 46:37.000
That's one way.

46:37.000 --> 46:39.000
But the other thing we need talk of meanings for

46:39.000 --> 46:41.000
is to say when things have the same meaning.

46:41.000 --> 46:46.000
And so it's that, and then we have identity, basically,

46:46.000 --> 46:49.000
which is a matter here of saying when things have the same meaning,

46:49.000 --> 46:54.000
we can talk about synonymy.

46:54.000 --> 46:58.000
And so in general, this becomes his strategy.

46:58.000 --> 47:03.000
We say, first there's the existence question,

47:03.000 --> 47:06.000
whether something has a meaning or not.

47:06.000 --> 47:08.000
And secondly, the identity question,

47:08.000 --> 47:11.000
when does this have the same meaning as that?

47:11.000 --> 47:13.000
And he's going to do that with all sorts of things.

47:13.000 --> 47:15.000
Propositions.

47:15.000 --> 47:18.000
It'll just be when does something express a proposition,

47:18.000 --> 47:22.000
and then when does it express the same proposition.

47:22.000 --> 47:26.000
So it will not be essentially equivalent to talking about meanings.

47:26.000 --> 47:27.000
And in the end, all we have to do is talk about

47:27.000 --> 47:29.000
significant or insignificant sentences,

47:29.000 --> 47:32.000
and then sentences meaning the same as other sentences.

47:32.000 --> 47:34.000
So that's the general recipe he's going to use

47:34.000 --> 47:36.000
for a lot of these abstract objects.

47:36.000 --> 47:40.000
Just introduce a way of talking about the existence of such a thing,

47:40.000 --> 47:42.000
and then what is that, the same one of those,

47:42.000 --> 47:45.000
and there's no need any longer to talk about the propositions

47:45.000 --> 47:48.000
or the facts or the attributes of the meanings.

